# Introduction

This assignment explores two fundamental topics in computer science: selection algorithms and elementary data structures. Selection algorithms are used to determine the kth smallest element in a collection of data, while elementary data structures provide efficient methods for organizing, storing, and manipulating information.

The assignment is divided into two parts. The first part focuses on implementing and analyzing deterministic and randomized selection algorithms. The second part focuses on implementing basic data structures including arrays, stacks, queues, and linked lists while evaluating their performance and practical applications.

---

# Part 1: Selection Algorithms

## Objective

The objective of this section is to implement algorithms capable of finding the kth smallest element in an unsorted array and analyze their theoretical and practical performance.

The following algorithms were implemented:

1. Randomized Quickselect
2. Deterministic Median-of-Medians

---

# Randomized Quickselect

## Overview

Randomized Quickselect is a selection algorithm based on the partitioning strategy used in Quicksort. Instead of sorting the entire array, it recursively processes only the partition containing the desired element.

The algorithm works as follows:

1. Randomly select a pivot element.
2. Partition the array around the pivot.
3. Determine which partition contains the kth smallest element.
4. Recursively search only the relevant partition.

---

## Advantages

* Simple implementation
* Excellent average-case performance
* Very efficient in practice
* Low memory overhead

---

## Disadvantages

* Worst-case running time is O(n²)
* Performance depends on pivot selection

---

## Time Complexity Analysis

### Best Case

When the pivot divides the array into nearly equal halves:

T(n) = T(n/2) + O(n)

Result:

O(n)

### Average Case

Random pivots typically create balanced partitions.

Expected Running Time:

O(n)

### Worst Case

Occurs when the pivot repeatedly becomes the smallest or largest element.

T(n) = T(n − 1) + O(n)

Result:

O(n²)

---

## Space Complexity

Average recursion depth:

O(log n)

Worst-case recursion depth:

O(n)

---

# Deterministic Median-of-Medians Algorithm

## Overview

The Median-of-Medians algorithm guarantees worst-case linear time selection.

The algorithm operates as follows:

1. Divide the array into groups of five elements.
2. Find the median of each group.
3. Recursively determine the median of those medians.
4. Use this value as the pivot.
5. Partition the array.
6. Continue recursively in the appropriate partition.

---

## Advantages

* Guaranteed O(n) worst-case performance
* Predictable execution time
* Suitable for critical systems requiring consistent performance

---

## Disadvantages

* More complicated implementation
* Larger constant factors
* Usually slower than Quickselect in practical applications

---

## Time Complexity Analysis

The recurrence relation is:

T(n) = T(n/5) + T(7n/10) + O(n)

The algorithm guarantees that at least 30% of elements are discarded during each recursive step.

Solving the recurrence gives:

T(n) = O(n)

---

## Space Complexity

The algorithm creates additional sublists during partitioning.

Auxiliary Space:

O(n)

---

# Comparison of Selection Algorithms

| Feature         | Randomized Quickselect | Median of Medians |
| --------------- | ---------------------- | ----------------- |
| Best Case       | O(n)                   | O(n)              |
| Average Case    | O(n)                   | O(n)              |
| Worst Case      | O(n²)                  | O(n)              |
| Practical Speed | Faster                 | Slower            |
| Implementation  | Simple                 | Complex           |
| Predictability  | Lower                  | Higher            |

---

# Empirical Analysis

## Experimental Setup

The algorithms were tested using arrays of different sizes:

* 1,000 elements
* 5,000 elements
* 10,000 elements
* 50,000 elements

Input distributions included:

* Random arrays
* Sorted arrays
* Reverse-sorted arrays

The median element was selected in each experiment.

---

## Observed Results

The experiments showed that Randomized Quickselect consistently performed faster than the Median-of-Medians algorithm on most datasets.

This behavior occurs because:

* Quickselect performs fewer computations.
* Median-of-Medians requires additional grouping and recursive median calculations.
* Constant factors significantly impact practical performance.

However, Median-of-Medians maintained stable performance regardless of input arrangement and guaranteed linear running time.

---

## Discussion

Although Median-of-Medians provides superior theoretical guarantees, Randomized Quickselect is generally preferred in real-world applications due to its simplicity and speed.

The deterministic algorithm becomes valuable in environments where worst-case guarantees are critical, such as real-time systems and security-sensitive applications.

