# Part 2: Elementary Data Structures

## Objective

The goal of this section is to implement and analyze several fundamental data structures commonly used in software development and algorithm design.

The following structures were implemented:

1. Arrays
2. Stacks
3. Queues
4. Singly Linked Lists

---

# Arrays

## Overview

An array stores elements in contiguous memory locations, enabling efficient random access.

Implemented Operations:

* Insertion
* Deletion
* Access

---

## Time Complexity

| Operation    | Complexity |
| ------------ | ---------- |
| Access       | O(1)       |
| Insert (End) | O(1)       |
| Delete       | O(n)       |
| Search       | O(n)       |

---

## Applications

* Image processing
* Scientific computing
* Databases
* Matrix operations

---

# Stacks

## Overview

A stack follows the Last-In-First-Out (LIFO) principle.

Implemented Operations:

* Push
* Pop
* Peek
* Is Empty

---

## Time Complexity

| Operation | Complexity |
| --------- | ---------- |
| Push      | O(1)       |
| Pop       | O(1)       |
| Peek      | O(1)       |

---

## Applications

* Function call management
* Undo operations
* Expression evaluation
* Syntax parsing

---

# Queues

## Overview

A queue follows the First-In-First-Out (FIFO) principle.

Implemented Operations:

* Enqueue
* Dequeue
* Is Empty

---

## Time Complexity

| Operation | Complexity |
| --------- | ---------- |
| Enqueue   | O(1)       |
| Dequeue   | O(n)       |

---

## Applications

* Process scheduling
* Task management systems
* Network packet buffering
* Printer queues

---

# Singly Linked Lists

## Overview

A linked list consists of nodes connected through references.

Each node contains:

* Data
* Pointer to the next node

Implemented Operations:

* Insertion
* Deletion
* Traversal

---

## Time Complexity

| Operation | Complexity                      |
| --------- | ------------------------------- |
| Insert    | O(1) at end (with tail pointer) |
| Delete    | O(n)                            |
| Search    | O(n)                            |
| Traverse  | O(n)                            |

---

## Applications

* Dynamic memory allocation
* Graph representations
* File systems
* Operating systems

---

# Arrays vs Linked Lists

| Feature         | Array      | Linked List    |
| --------------- | ---------- | -------------- |
| Memory Layout   | Contiguous | Non-Contiguous |
| Access Time     | O(1)       | O(n)           |
| Insertion       | O(n)       | O(1)           |
| Deletion        | O(n)       | O(1)           |
| Memory Overhead | Low        | Higher         |

---

# Stacks and Queues: Array vs Linked List

## Arrays

Advantages:

* Faster access
* Better cache performance
* Simpler implementation

Disadvantages:

* Fixed-size limitations in some implementations
* Expensive front insertions and deletions

## Linked Lists

Advantages:

* Dynamic growth
* Efficient insertion and deletion

Disadvantages:

* Extra memory consumption
* Slower traversal

---

# Practical Applications

Choosing the correct data structure depends on the application's requirements.

Arrays are preferred when:

* Fast indexing is needed.
* Memory locality is important.

Linked Lists are preferred when:

* Frequent insertions and deletions occur.

Stacks are preferred when:

* Reversing operations.
* Managing recursive calls.

Queues are preferred when:

* Maintaining processing order.
* Scheduling tasks.

---

# Conclusion

This assignment provided practical experience implementing selection algorithms and elementary data structures.

The Randomized Quickselect algorithm demonstrated excellent practical performance with expected linear running time, while the Median-of-Medians algorithm provided guaranteed worst-case linear performance.

The implementation of arrays, stacks, queues, and linked lists reinforced fundamental concepts related to data organization and algorithm efficiency. Understanding the strengths and weaknesses of these structures is essential for designing efficient software systems.

Overall, the assignment highlighted the importance of selecting appropriate algorithms and data structures based on performance requirements, memory constraints, and application-specific needs.
